4175/* C++: all of these are overloaded! These apply only to TYPE_DECLs. */
4176
4177/* The format of each node in the DECL_FRIENDLIST is as follows:
4178
4179 The TREE_PURPOSE will be the name of a function, i.e., an
4180 IDENTIFIER_NODE. The TREE_VALUE will be itself a TREE_LIST, whose
4181 TREE_VALUEs are friends with the given name. */
4182#define DECL_FRIENDLIST(NODE) (DECL_INITIAL (NODE))
4183#define FRIEND_NAME(LIST) (TREE_PURPOSE (LIST))
4184#define FRIEND_DECLS(LIST) (TREE_VALUE (LIST))
4185
4186/* The DECL_ACCESS, if non-NULL, is a TREE_LIST. The TREE_PURPOSE of
4187 each node is a type; the TREE_VALUE is the access granted for this
4188 DECL in that type. The DECL_ACCESS is set by access declarations.
4189 For example, if a member that would normally be public in a
4190 derived class is made protected, then the derived class and the
4191 protected_access_node will appear in the DECL_ACCESS for the node. */
4192#define DECL_ACCESS(NODE) (LANG_DECL_U2_CHECK (NODE, 0)->access)
4193
4194/* Nonzero if the FUNCTION_DECL is a global constructor. */
4195#define DECL_GLOBAL_CTOR_P(NODE) \
4196 (LANG_DECL_FN_CHECK (NODE)->global_ctor_p)
4197
4198/* Nonzero if the FUNCTION_DECL is a global destructor. */
4199#define DECL_GLOBAL_DTOR_P(NODE) \
4200 (LANG_DECL_FN_CHECK (NODE)->global_dtor_p)

4202/* Accessor macros for C++ template decl nodes. */
4203
4204/* The DECL_TEMPLATE_PARMS are a list. The TREE_PURPOSE of each node
4205 is a INT_CST whose TREE_INT_CST_LOW indicates the level of the
4206 template parameters, with 1 being the outermost set of template
4207 parameters. The TREE_VALUE is a vector, whose elements are the
4208 template parameters at each level. Each element in the vector is a
4209 TREE_LIST, whose TREE_VALUE is a PARM_DECL (if the parameter is a
4210 non-type parameter), or a TYPE_DECL (if the parameter is a type
4211 parameter). The TREE_PURPOSE is the default value, if any. The
4212 TEMPLATE_PARM_INDEX for the parameter is available as the
4213 DECL_INITIAL (for a PARM_DECL) or as the TREE_TYPE (for a
4214 TYPE_DECL).
4215
4216 FIXME: CONST_CAST_TREE is a hack that hopefully will go away after
4217 tree is converted to C++ class hiearchy. */
4218#define DECL_TEMPLATE_PARMS(NODE) \
4219 ((struct tree_template_decl *)CONST_CAST_TREE (TEMPLATE_DECL_CHECK (NODE)))->arguments
4220#define DECL_INNERMOST_TEMPLATE_PARMS(NODE) \
4221 INNERMOST_TEMPLATE_PARMS (DECL_TEMPLATE_PARMS (NODE))
4222#define DECL_NTPARMS(NODE) \
4223 TREE_VEC_LENGTH (DECL_INNERMOST_TEMPLATE_PARMS (NODE))
4224/* For function, method, class-data templates.
4225
4226 FIXME: CONST_CAST_TREE is a hack that hopefully will go away after
4227 tree is converted to C++ class hiearchy. */
4228#define DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT(NODE) \
4229 ((struct tree_template_decl *)CONST_CAST_TREE(TEMPLATE_DECL_CHECK (NODE)))->result
4230/* For a function template at namespace scope, DECL_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATIONS
4231 lists all instantiations and specializations of the function so that
4232 tsubst_friend_function can reassign them to another template if we find
4233 that the namespace-scope template is really a partial instantiation of a
4234 friend template.
4235
4236 For a class template the DECL_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATIONS lists holds
4237 all instantiations and specializations of the class type, including
4238 partial instantiations and partial specializations, so that if we
4239 explicitly specialize a partial instantiation we can walk the list
4240 in maybe_process_partial_specialization and reassign them or complain
4241 as appropriate.
4242
4243 In both cases, the TREE_PURPOSE of each node contains the arguments
4244 used; the TREE_VALUE contains the generated variable. The template
4245 arguments are always complete. For example, given:
4246
4247 template <class T> struct S1 {
4248 template <class U> struct S2 {};
4249 template <class U> struct S2<U*> {};
4250 };
4251
4252 the record for the partial specialization will contain, as its
4253 argument list, { {T}, {U*} }, and will be on the
4254 DECL_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATIONS list for `template <class T> template
4255 <class U> struct S1<T>::S2'.
4256
4257 This list is not used for other templates. */
4258#define DECL_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATIONS(NODE) \
4259 DECL_SIZE_UNIT (TEMPLATE_DECL_CHECK (NODE))
4260
4261/* For a class template, this list contains the partial
4262 specializations of this template. (Full specializations are not
4263 recorded on this list.) The TREE_PURPOSE holds the arguments used
4264 in the partial specialization (e.g., for `template <class T> struct
4265 S<T*, int>' this will be `T*, int'.) The arguments will also include
4266 any outer template arguments. The TREE_VALUE holds the TEMPLATE_DECL
4267 for the partial specialization. The TREE_TYPE is the _TYPE node for
4268 the partial specialization.
4269
4270 This list is not used for other templates. */
4271#define DECL_TEMPLATE_SPECIALIZATIONS(NODE) \
4272 DECL_SIZE (TEMPLATE_DECL_CHECK (NODE))
4273
4274/* Nonzero for a DECL which is actually a template parameter. Keep
4275 these checks in ascending tree code order. */
4276#define DECL_TEMPLATE_PARM_P(NODE) \
4277 (DECL_LANG_FLAG_0 (NODE) \
4278 && (TREE_CODE (NODE) == CONST_DECL \
4279 || TREE_CODE (NODE) == PARM_DECL \
4280 || TREE_CODE (NODE) == TYPE_DECL \
4281 || TREE_CODE (NODE) == TEMPLATE_DECL))
4282
4283/* Mark NODE as a template parameter. */
4284#define SET_DECL_TEMPLATE_PARM_P(NODE) \
4285 (DECL_LANG_FLAG_0 (NODE) = 1)
4286
4287/* Nonzero if NODE is a template template parameter. */
4288#define DECL_TEMPLATE_TEMPLATE_PARM_P(NODE) \
4289 (TREE_CODE (NODE) == TEMPLATE_DECL && DECL_TEMPLATE_PARM_P (NODE))
4290
4291/* Nonzero for a DECL that represents a function template. */
4292#define DECL_FUNCTION_TEMPLATE_P(NODE) \
4293 (TREE_CODE (NODE) == TEMPLATE_DECL \
4294 && DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT (NODE) != NULL_TREE \
4295 && TREE_CODE (DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT (NODE)) == FUNCTION_DECL)
4296
4297/* Nonzero for a DECL that represents a class template or alias
4298 template. */
4299#define DECL_TYPE_TEMPLATE_P(NODE) \
4300 (TREE_CODE (NODE) == TEMPLATE_DECL \
4301 && DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT (NODE) != NULL_TREE \
4302 && TREE_CODE (DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT (NODE)) == TYPE_DECL)
4303
4304/* Nonzero for a DECL that represents a class template. */
4305#define DECL_CLASS_TEMPLATE_P(NODE) \
4306 (DECL_TYPE_TEMPLATE_P (NODE) \
4307 && DECL_IMPLICIT_TYPEDEF_P (DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT (NODE)))
4308
4309/* Nonzero for a TEMPLATE_DECL that represents an alias template. */
4310#define DECL_ALIAS_TEMPLATE_P(NODE) \
4311 (DECL_TYPE_TEMPLATE_P (NODE) \
4312 && !DECL_ARTIFICIAL (DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT (NODE)))
4313
4314/* Nonzero for a NODE which declares a type. */
4315#define DECL_DECLARES_TYPE_P(NODE) \
4316 (TREE_CODE (NODE) == TYPE_DECL || DECL_TYPE_TEMPLATE_P (NODE))
4317
4318/* Nonzero if NODE declares a function. */
4319#define DECL_DECLARES_FUNCTION_P(NODE) \
4320 (TREE_CODE (NODE) == FUNCTION_DECL || DECL_FUNCTION_TEMPLATE_P (NODE))
4321
4322/* Nonzero if NODE is the typedef implicitly generated for a type when
4323 the type is declared. In C++, `struct S {};' is roughly
4324 equivalent to `struct S {}; typedef struct S S;' in C.
4325 DECL_IMPLICIT_TYPEDEF_P will hold for the typedef indicated in this
4326 example. In C++, there is a second implicit typedef for each
4327 class, called the injected-class-name, in the scope of `S' itself, so that
4328 you can say `S::S'. DECL_SELF_REFERENCE_P will hold for that typedef. */
4329#define DECL_IMPLICIT_TYPEDEF_P(NODE) \
4330 (TREE_CODE (NODE) == TYPE_DECL && DECL_LANG_FLAG_2 (NODE))
4331#define SET_DECL_IMPLICIT_TYPEDEF_P(NODE) \
4332 (DECL_LANG_FLAG_2 (NODE) = 1)
4333#define DECL_SELF_REFERENCE_P(NODE) \
4334 (TREE_CODE (NODE) == TYPE_DECL && DECL_LANG_FLAG_4 (NODE))
4335#define SET_DECL_SELF_REFERENCE_P(NODE) \
4336 (DECL_LANG_FLAG_4 (NODE) = 1)
4337
4338/* A `primary' template is one that has its own template header and is not
4339 a partial specialization. A member function of a class template is a
4340 template, but not primary. A member template is primary. Friend
4341 templates are primary, too. */
4342
4343/* Returns the primary template corresponding to these parameters. */
4344#define DECL_PRIMARY_TEMPLATE(NODE) \
4345 (TREE_TYPE (DECL_INNERMOST_TEMPLATE_PARMS (NODE)))
4346
4347/* Returns nonzero if NODE is a primary template. */
4348#define PRIMARY_TEMPLATE_P(NODE) (DECL_PRIMARY_TEMPLATE (NODE) == (NODE))
4349
4350/* Nonzero iff NODE is a specialization of a template. The value
4351 indicates the type of specializations:
4352
4353 1=implicit instantiation
4354
4355 2=partial or explicit specialization, e.g.:
4356
4357 template <> int min<int> (int, int),
4358
4359 3=explicit instantiation, e.g.:
4360
4361 template int min<int> (int, int);
4362
4363 Note that NODE will be marked as a specialization even if the
4364 template it is instantiating is not a primary template. For
4365 example, given:
4366
4367 template <typename T> struct O {
4368 void f();
4369 struct I {};
4370 };
4371
4372 both O<int>::f and O<int>::I will be marked as instantiations.
4373
4374 If DECL_USE_TEMPLATE is nonzero, then DECL_TEMPLATE_INFO will also
4375 be non-NULL. */
4376#define DECL_USE_TEMPLATE(NODE) (DECL_LANG_SPECIFIC (NODE)->u.base.use_template)
4377
4378/* Like DECL_USE_TEMPLATE, but for class types. */
4379#define CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE(NODE) \
4380 (LANG_TYPE_CLASS_CHECK (NODE)->use_template)
4381
4382/* True if NODE is a specialization of a primary template. */
4383#define CLASSTYPE_SPECIALIZATION_OF_PRIMARY_TEMPLATE_P(NODE) \
4384 (CLASS_TYPE_P (NODE) \
4385 && CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) \
4386 && PRIMARY_TEMPLATE_P (CLASSTYPE_TI_TEMPLATE (NODE)))
4387
4388#define DECL_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATION(NODE) (DECL_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) & 1)
4389#define CLASSTYPE_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATION(NODE) \
4390 (CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) & 1)
4391
4392#define DECL_TEMPLATE_SPECIALIZATION(NODE) (DECL_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) == 2)
4393#define SET_DECL_TEMPLATE_SPECIALIZATION(NODE) (DECL_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) = 2)
4394
4395/* Returns true for an explicit or partial specialization of a class
4396 template. */
4397#define CLASSTYPE_TEMPLATE_SPECIALIZATION(NODE) \
4398 (CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) == 2)
4399#define SET_CLASSTYPE_TEMPLATE_SPECIALIZATION(NODE) \
4400 (CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) = 2)
4401
4402#define DECL_IMPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) (DECL_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) == 1)
4403#define SET_DECL_IMPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) (DECL_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) = 1)
4404#define CLASSTYPE_IMPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) \
4405 (CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) == 1)
4406#define SET_CLASSTYPE_IMPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) \
4407 (CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) = 1)
4408
4409#define DECL_EXPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) (DECL_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) == 3)
4410#define SET_DECL_EXPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) (DECL_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) = 3)
4411#define CLASSTYPE_EXPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) \
4412 (CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) == 3)
4413#define SET_CLASSTYPE_EXPLICIT_INSTANTIATION(NODE) \
4414 (CLASSTYPE_USE_TEMPLATE (NODE) = 3)
4415
4416/* Nonzero if DECL is a friend function which is an instantiation
4417 from the point of view of the compiler, but not from the point of
4418 view of the language. For example given:
4419 template <class T> struct S { friend void f(T) {}; };
4420 the declaration of `void f(int)' generated when S<int> is
4421 instantiated will not be a DECL_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATION, but will be
4422 a DECL_FRIEND_PSEUDO_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATION. */
4423#define DECL_FRIEND_PSEUDO_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATION(DECL) \
4424 (DECL_LANG_SPECIFIC (DECL) && DECL_TEMPLATE_INFO (DECL) \
4425 && !DECL_USE_TEMPLATE (DECL))
4426
4427/* Nonzero if DECL is a function generated from a function 'temploid',
4428 i.e. template, member of class template, or dependent friend. */
4429#define DECL_TEMPLOID_INSTANTIATION(DECL) \
4430 (DECL_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATION (DECL) \
4431 || DECL_FRIEND_PSEUDO_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATION (DECL))
4432
4433/* Nonzero if DECL is either defined implicitly by the compiler or
4434 generated from a temploid. */
4435#define DECL_GENERATED_P(DECL) \
4436 (DECL_TEMPLOID_INSTANTIATION (DECL) || DECL_DEFAULTED_FN (DECL))
4437
4438/* Nonzero iff we are currently processing a declaration for an
4439 entity with its own template parameter list, and which is not a
4440 full specialization. */
4441#define PROCESSING_REAL_TEMPLATE_DECL_P() \
4442 (processing_template_decl > template_class_depth (current_scope ()))
4443
4444/* Nonzero if this VAR_DECL or FUNCTION_DECL has already been
4445 instantiated, i.e. its definition has been generated from the
4446 pattern given in the template. */
4447#define DECL_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATED(NODE) \
4448 DECL_LANG_FLAG_1 (VAR_OR_FUNCTION_DECL_CHECK (NODE))
4449
4450/* We know what we're doing with this decl now. */
4451#define DECL_INTERFACE_KNOWN(NODE) DECL_LANG_FLAG_5 (NODE)
4452
4453/* DECL_EXTERNAL must be set on a decl until the decl is actually emitted,
4454 so that assemble_external will work properly. So we have this flag to
4455 tell us whether the decl is really not external.
4456
4457 This flag does not indicate whether or not the decl is defined in the
4458 current translation unit; it indicates whether or not we should emit the
4459 decl at the end of compilation if it is defined and needed. */
4460#define DECL_NOT_REALLY_EXTERN(NODE) \
4461 (DECL_LANG_SPECIFIC (NODE)->u.base.not_really_extern)
4462
4463#define DECL_REALLY_EXTERN(NODE) \
4464 (DECL_EXTERNAL (NODE) \
4465 && (!DECL_LANG_SPECIFIC (NODE) || !DECL_NOT_REALLY_EXTERN (NODE)))

4467/* A thunk is a stub function.
4468
4469 A thunk is an alternate entry point for an ordinary FUNCTION_DECL.
4470 The address of the ordinary FUNCTION_DECL is given by the
4471 DECL_INITIAL, which is always an ADDR_EXPR whose operand is a
4472 FUNCTION_DECL. The job of the thunk is to either adjust the this
4473 pointer before transferring control to the FUNCTION_DECL, or call
4474 FUNCTION_DECL and then adjust the result value. Note, the result
4475 pointer adjusting thunk must perform a call to the thunked
4476 function, (or be implemented via passing some invisible parameter
4477 to the thunked function, which is modified to perform the
4478 adjustment just before returning).
4479
4480 A thunk may perform either, or both, of the following operations:
4481
4482 o Adjust the this or result pointer by a constant offset.
4483 o Adjust the this or result pointer by looking up a vcall or vbase offset
4484 in the vtable.
4485
4486 A this pointer adjusting thunk converts from a base to a derived
4487 class, and hence adds the offsets. A result pointer adjusting thunk
4488 converts from a derived class to a base, and hence subtracts the
4489 offsets. If both operations are performed, then the constant
4490 adjustment is performed first for this pointer adjustment and last
4491 for the result pointer adjustment.
4492
4493 The constant adjustment is given by THUNK_FIXED_OFFSET. If the
4494 vcall or vbase offset is required, THUNK_VIRTUAL_OFFSET is
4495 used. For this pointer adjusting thunks, it is the vcall offset
4496 into the vtable. For result pointer adjusting thunks it is the
4497 binfo of the virtual base to convert to. Use that binfo's vbase
4498 offset.
4499
4500 It is possible to have equivalent covariant thunks. These are
4501 distinct virtual covariant thunks whose vbase offsets happen to
4502 have the same value. THUNK_ALIAS is used to pick one as the
4503 canonical thunk, which will get all the this pointer adjusting
4504 thunks attached to it. */
4505
4506/* An integer indicating how many bytes should be subtracted from the
4507 this or result pointer when this function is called. */
4508#define THUNK_FIXED_OFFSET(DECL) \
4509 (DECL_LANG_SPECIFIC (THUNK_FUNCTION_CHECK (DECL))->u.fn.u5.fixed_offset)
4510
4511/* A tree indicating how to perform the virtual adjustment. For a this
4512 adjusting thunk it is the number of bytes to be added to the vtable
4513 to find the vcall offset. For a result adjusting thunk, it is the
4514 binfo of the relevant virtual base. If NULL, then there is no
4515 virtual adjust. (The vptr is always located at offset zero from
4516 the this or result pointer.) (If the covariant type is within the
4517 class hierarchy being laid out, the vbase index is not yet known
4518 at the point we need to create the thunks, hence the need to use
4519 binfos.) */
4520
4521#define THUNK_VIRTUAL_OFFSET(DECL) \
4522 (LANG_DECL_U2_CHECK (FUNCTION_DECL_CHECK (DECL), 0)->access)
4523
4524/* A thunk which is equivalent to another thunk. */
4525#define THUNK_ALIAS(DECL) \
4526 (DECL_LANG_SPECIFIC (FUNCTION_DECL_CHECK (DECL))->u.min.template_info)
4527
4528/* For thunk NODE, this is the FUNCTION_DECL thunked to. It is
4529 possible for the target to be a thunk too. */
4530#define THUNK_TARGET(NODE) \
4531 (LANG_DECL_FN_CHECK (NODE)->befriending_classes)
4532
4533/* True for a SCOPE_REF iff the "template" keyword was used to
4534 indicate that the qualified name denotes a template. */
4535#define QUALIFIED_NAME_IS_TEMPLATE(NODE) \
4536 (TREE_LANG_FLAG_1 (SCOPE_REF_CHECK (NODE)))

4538/* True for an OMP_ATOMIC that has dependent parameters. These are stored

4540#define OMP_ATOMIC_DEPENDENT_P(NODE) \

4706/* The various kinds of access. BINFO_ACCESS depends on these being

4712 ak_public = 1, /* Accessible, as a `public' thing. */
4713 ak_protected = 2, /* Accessible, as a `protected' thing. */
4714 ak_private = 3 /* Accessible, as a `private' thing. */

4718 you should update special_function_p as well. */

4721 must have value zero; see
4722 special_function_p. */
4723 sfk_constructor, /* A constructor. */
4724 sfk_copy_constructor, /* A copy constructor. */
4725 sfk_move_constructor, /* A move constructor. */
4726 sfk_copy_assignment, /* A copy assignment operator. */
4727 sfk_move_assignment, /* A move assignment operator. */
4728 sfk_destructor, /* A destructor. */
4729 sfk_complete_destructor, /* A destructor for complete objects. */
4730 sfk_base_destructor, /* A destructor for base subobjects. */
4731 sfk_deleting_destructor, /* A destructor for complete objects that
4732 deletes the object after it has been
4733 destroyed. */

4739/* The various kinds of linkage. From [basic.link],
4740
4741 A name is said to have linkage when it might denote the same
4742 object, reference, function, type, template, namespace or value
4743 as a name introduced in another scope:
4744
4745 -- When a name has external linkage, the entity it denotes can
4746 be referred to from scopes of other translation units or from
4747 other scopes of the same translation unit.
4748
4749 -- When a name has internal linkage, the entity it denotes can
4750 be referred to by names from other scopes in the same
4751 translation unit.
4752
4753 -- When a name has no linkage, the entity it denotes cannot be
4754 referred to by names from other scopes. */
4755
4756enum linkage_kind {
4757 lk_none, /* No linkage. */
4758 lk_internal, /* Internal linkage. */
4759 lk_external /* External linkage. */
4760};

4769/* Bitmask flags to control type substitution. */
4770enum tsubst_flags {
4771 tf_none = 0, /* nothing special */
4772 tf_error = 1 << 0, /* give error messages */
4773 tf_warning = 1 << 1, /* give warnings too */
4774 tf_ignore_bad_quals = 1 << 2, /* ignore bad cvr qualifiers */
4775 tf_keep_type_decl = 1 << 3, /* retain typedef type decls
4776 (make_typename_type use) */
4777 tf_ptrmem_ok = 1 << 4, /* pointers to member ok (internal
4778 instantiate_type use) */
4779 tf_user = 1 << 5, /* found template must be a user template
4780 (lookup_template_class use) */
4781 tf_conv = 1 << 6, /* We are determining what kind of
4782 conversion might be permissible,
4783 not actually performing the
4784 conversion. */
4785 tf_decltype = 1 << 7, /* We are the operand of decltype.
4786 Used to implement the special rules
4787 for calls in decltype (5.2.2/11). */
4788 tf_partial = 1 << 8, /* Doing initial explicit argument
4789 substitution in fn_type_unification. */
4790 tf_fndecl_type = 1 << 9, /* Substituting the type of a function
4791 declaration. */
4792 tf_no_cleanup = 1 << 10, /* Do not build a cleanup
4793 (build_target_expr and friends) */
4794 /* Convenient substitution flags combinations. */
4795 tf_warning_or_error = tf_warning | tf_error
4796};

4799 combinations of the flags in enum tsubst_flags. */

4802/* The kind of checking we can do looking in a class hierarchy. */

4805 prefer a non-virtual base */

4807 ba_check_bit = 1 << 1, /* Check access. */
4808 ba_check = ba_unique | ba_check_bit,
4809 ba_ignore_scope = 1 << 2 /* Ignore access allowed by local scope. */

4903/* Cannot use '$' up front, because this confuses gdb
4904 (names beginning with '$' are gdb-local identifiers).
4905
4906 Note that all forms in which the '$' is significant are long enough
4907 for direct indexing (meaning that if we know there is a '$'
4908 at a particular location, we can index into the string at
4909 any other location that provides distinguishing characters). */

4911/* Define NO_DOT_IN_LABEL in your favorite tm file if your assembler
4912 doesn't allow '.' in symbol names. */

4916
4917#define AUTO_TEMP_NAME "_.tmp_"
4918#define VFIELD_BASE ".vf"
4919#define VFIELD_NAME "_vptr."
4920#define VFIELD_NAME_FORMAT "_vptr.%s"

4922#else /* NO_DOT_IN_LABEL */

4927

4929#define VFIELD_BASE "$vf"
4930#define VFIELD_NAME "_vptr$"
4931#define VFIELD_NAME_FORMAT "_vptr$%s"
4932
4933#else /* NO_DOLLAR_IN_LABEL */
4934

4936#define TEMP_NAME_P(ID_NODE) \
4937 (!strncmp (IDENTIFIER_POINTER (ID_NODE), AUTO_TEMP_NAME, \
4938 sizeof (AUTO_TEMP_NAME) - 1))
4939#define VTABLE_NAME "__vt_"
4940#define VTABLE_NAME_P(ID_NODE) \
4941 (!strncmp (IDENTIFIER_POINTER (ID_NODE), VTABLE_NAME, \
4942 sizeof (VTABLE_NAME) - 1))
4943#define VFIELD_BASE "__vfb"
4944#define VFIELD_NAME "__vptr_"
4945#define VFIELD_NAME_P(ID_NODE) \
4946 (!strncmp (IDENTIFIER_POINTER (ID_NODE), VFIELD_NAME, \
4947 sizeof (VFIELD_NAME) - 1))
4948#define VFIELD_NAME_FORMAT "__vptr_%s"
4949
4950#endif /* NO_DOLLAR_IN_LABEL */
4951#endif /* NO_DOT_IN_LABEL */

5003/* A list of namespace-scope objects which have constructors or
5004 destructors which reside in the global scope. The decl is stored
5005 in the TREE_VALUE slot and the initializer is stored in the
5006 TREE_PURPOSE slot. */

5010
5011enum overload_flags { NO_SPECIAL = 0, DTOR_FLAG, TYPENAME_FLAG };
5012
5013/* These are uses as bits in flags passed to various functions to
5014 control their behavior. Despite the LOOKUP_ prefix, many of these
5015 do not control name lookup. ??? Functions using these flags should
5016 probably be modified to accept explicit boolean flags for the
5017 behaviors relevant to them. */
5018/* Check for access violations. */
5019#define LOOKUP_PROTECT (1 << 0)
5020#define LOOKUP_NORMAL (LOOKUP_PROTECT)
5021/* Even if the function found by lookup is a virtual function, it
5022 should be called directly. */
5023#define LOOKUP_NONVIRTUAL (1 << 1)
5024/* Non-converting (i.e., "explicit") constructors are not tried. This flag
5025 indicates that we are not performing direct-initialization. */
5026#define LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING (1 << 2)
5027#define LOOKUP_IMPLICIT (LOOKUP_NORMAL | LOOKUP_ONLYCONVERTING)
5028/* If a temporary is created, it should be created so that it lives
5029 as long as the current variable bindings; otherwise it only lives
5030 until the end of the complete-expression. It also forces
5031 direct-initialization in cases where other parts of the compiler
5032 have already generated a temporary, such as reference
5033 initialization and the catch parameter. */
5034#define DIRECT_BIND (1 << 3)
5035/* We're performing a user-defined conversion, so more user-defined
5036 conversions are not permitted (only built-in conversions). */
5037#define LOOKUP_NO_CONVERSION (1 << 4)
5038/* The user has explicitly called a destructor. (Therefore, we do
5039 not need to check that the object is non-NULL before calling the
5040 destructor.) */
5041#define LOOKUP_DESTRUCTOR (1 << 5)
5042/* Do not permit references to bind to temporaries. */
5043#define LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND (1 << 6)
5044/* Do not accept objects, and possibly namespaces. */
5045#define LOOKUP_PREFER_TYPES (1 << 7)
5046/* Do not accept objects, and possibly types. */
5047#define LOOKUP_PREFER_NAMESPACES (1 << 8)
5048/* Accept types or namespaces. */
5049#define LOOKUP_PREFER_BOTH (LOOKUP_PREFER_TYPES | LOOKUP_PREFER_NAMESPACES)
5050/* Return friend declarations and un-declared builtin functions.
5051 (Normally, these entities are registered in the symbol table, but
5052 not found by lookup.) */
5053#define LOOKUP_HIDDEN (LOOKUP_PREFER_NAMESPACES << 1)
5054/* Prefer that the lvalue be treated as an rvalue. */
5055#define LOOKUP_PREFER_RVALUE (LOOKUP_HIDDEN << 1)
5056/* We're inside an init-list, so narrowing conversions are ill-formed. */
5057#define LOOKUP_NO_NARROWING (LOOKUP_PREFER_RVALUE << 1)
5058/* We're looking up a constructor for list-initialization. */
5059#define LOOKUP_LIST_INIT_CTOR (LOOKUP_NO_NARROWING << 1)
5060/* This is the first parameter of a copy constructor. */
5061#define LOOKUP_COPY_PARM (LOOKUP_LIST_INIT_CTOR << 1)
5062/* We only want to consider list constructors. */
5063#define LOOKUP_LIST_ONLY (LOOKUP_COPY_PARM << 1)
5064/* Return after determining which function to call and checking access.
5065 Used by sythesized_method_walk to determine which functions will
5066 be called to initialize subobjects, in order to determine exception
5067 specification and possible implicit delete.
5068 This is kind of a hack, but exiting early avoids problems with trying
5069 to perform argument conversions when the class isn't complete yet. */
5070#define LOOKUP_SPECULATIVE (LOOKUP_LIST_ONLY << 1)
5071/* Used by calls from defaulted functions to limit the overload set to avoid
5072 cycles trying to declare them (core issue 1092). */
5073#define LOOKUP_DEFAULTED (LOOKUP_SPECULATIVE << 1)
5074/* Used in calls to store_init_value to suppress its usual call to
5075 digest_init. */
5076#define LOOKUP_ALREADY_DIGESTED (LOOKUP_DEFAULTED << 1)
5077/* An instantiation with explicit template arguments. */
5078#define LOOKUP_EXPLICIT_TMPL_ARGS (LOOKUP_ALREADY_DIGESTED << 1)
5079/* Like LOOKUP_NO_TEMP_BIND, but also prevent binding to xvalues. */
5080#define LOOKUP_NO_RVAL_BIND (LOOKUP_EXPLICIT_TMPL_ARGS << 1)
5081/* Used by case_conversion to disregard non-integral conversions. */
5082#define LOOKUP_NO_NON_INTEGRAL (LOOKUP_NO_RVAL_BIND << 1)
5083/* Used for delegating constructors in order to diagnose self-delegation. */
5084#define LOOKUP_DELEGATING_CONS (LOOKUP_NO_NON_INTEGRAL << 1)
5085
5086#define LOOKUP_NAMESPACES_ONLY(F) \
5087 (((F) & LOOKUP_PREFER_NAMESPACES) && !((F) & LOOKUP_PREFER_TYPES))
5088#define LOOKUP_TYPES_ONLY(F) \
5089 (!((F) & LOOKUP_PREFER_NAMESPACES) && ((F) & LOOKUP_PREFER_TYPES))
5090#define LOOKUP_QUALIFIERS_ONLY(F) ((F) & LOOKUP_PREFER_BOTH)
5091
5092
5093/* These flags are used by the conversion code.
5094 CONV_IMPLICIT : Perform implicit conversions (standard and user-defined).
5095 CONV_STATIC : Perform the explicit conversions for static_cast.
5096 CONV_CONST : Perform the explicit conversions for const_cast.
5097 CONV_REINTERPRET: Perform the explicit conversions for reinterpret_cast.
5098 CONV_PRIVATE : Perform upcasts to private bases.
5099 CONV_FORCE_TEMP : Require a new temporary when converting to the same
5100 aggregate type. */
5101
5102#define CONV_IMPLICIT 1
5103#define CONV_STATIC 2
5104#define CONV_CONST 4
5105#define CONV_REINTERPRET 8
5106#define CONV_PRIVATE 16
5107/* #define CONV_NONCONVERTING 32 */
5108#define CONV_FORCE_TEMP 64
5109#define CONV_FOLD 128
5110#define CONV_OLD_CONVERT (CONV_IMPLICIT | CONV_STATIC | CONV_CONST \
5111 | CONV_REINTERPRET)
5112#define CONV_C_CAST (CONV_IMPLICIT | CONV_STATIC | CONV_CONST \
5113 | CONV_REINTERPRET | CONV_PRIVATE | CONV_FORCE_TEMP)
5114#define CONV_BACKEND_CONVERT (CONV_OLD_CONVERT | CONV_FOLD)

5116/* Used by build_expr_type_conversion to indicate which types are
5117 acceptable as arguments to the expression under consideration. */
5118
5119#define WANT_INT 1 /* integer types, including bool */
5120#define WANT_FLOAT 2 /* floating point types */
5121#define WANT_ENUM 4 /* enumerated types */
5122#define WANT_POINTER 8 /* pointer types */
5123#define WANT_NULL 16 /* null pointer constant */
5124#define WANT_VECTOR_OR_COMPLEX 32 /* vector or complex types */
5125#define WANT_ARITH (WANT_INT | WANT_FLOAT | WANT_VECTOR_OR_COMPLEX)

5127/* Used with comptypes, and related functions, to guide type
5128 comparison. */

5130#define COMPARE_STRICT 0 /* Just check if the types are the
5131 same. */
5132#define COMPARE_BASE 1 /* Check to see if the second type is
5133 derived from the first. */
5134#define COMPARE_DERIVED 2 /* Like COMPARE_BASE, but in
5135 reverse. */
5136#define COMPARE_REDECLARATION 4 /* The comparison is being done when
5137 another declaration of an existing
5138 entity is seen. */
5139#define COMPARE_STRUCTURAL 8 /* The comparison is intended to be
5140 structural. The actual comparison
5141 will be identical to
5142 COMPARE_STRICT. */

5148 scope. */
5149#define PUSH_USING 2 /* We are pushing this DECL as the

5165/* Returns nonzero iff TYPE1 and TYPE2 are the same type, or if TYPE2
5166 is derived from TYPE1, or if TYPE2 is a pointer (reference) to a
5167 class derived from the type pointed to (referred to) by TYPE1. */
5168#define same_or_base_type_p(TYPE1, TYPE2) \
5169 comptypes ((TYPE1), (TYPE2), COMPARE_BASE)

5192#define TEMPLATE_TYPE_ORIG_LEVEL(NODE) \
5193 (TEMPLATE_PARM_ORIG_LEVEL (TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARM_INDEX (NODE)))
5194#define TEMPLATE_TYPE_DECL(NODE) \
5195 (TEMPLATE_PARM_DECL (TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARM_INDEX (NODE)))
5196#define TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARAMETER_PACK(NODE) \
5197 (TEMPLATE_PARM_PARAMETER_PACK (TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARM_INDEX (NODE)))
5198
5199/* For a C++17 class deduction placeholder, the template it represents. */
5200#define CLASS_PLACEHOLDER_TEMPLATE(NODE) \
5201 (DECL_INITIAL (TYPE_NAME (TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARM_CHECK (NODE))))
5202
5203/* Contexts in which auto deduction occurs. These flags are
5204 used to control diagnostics in do_auto_deduction. */
5205
5206enum auto_deduction_context
5207{
5208 adc_unspecified, /* Not given */
5209 adc_variable_type, /* Variable initializer deduction */
5210 adc_return_type, /* Return type deduction */
5211 adc_unify, /* Template argument deduction */
5212 adc_requirement, /* Argument deduction constraint */
5213 adc_decomp_type /* Decomposition declaration initializer deduction */
5214};
5215
5216/* True if this type-parameter belongs to a class template, used by C++17
5217 class template argument deduction. */
5218#define TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARM_FOR_CLASS(NODE) \
5219 (TREE_LANG_FLAG_0 (TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARM_CHECK (NODE)))
5220
5221/* True iff this TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARM represents decltype(auto). */
5222#define AUTO_IS_DECLTYPE(NODE) \
5223 (TYPE_LANG_FLAG_5 (TEMPLATE_TYPE_PARM_CHECK (NODE)))
5224
5225/* These constants can used as bit flags in the process of tree formatting.
5226
5227 TFF_PLAIN_IDENTIFIER: unqualified part of a name.
5228 TFF_SCOPE: include the class and namespace scope of the name.
5229 TFF_CHASE_TYPEDEF: print the original type-id instead of the typedef-name.
5230 TFF_DECL_SPECIFIERS: print decl-specifiers.
5231 TFF_CLASS_KEY_OR_ENUM: precede a class-type name (resp. enum name) with
5232 a class-key (resp. `enum').
5233 TFF_RETURN_TYPE: include function return type.
5234 TFF_FUNCTION_DEFAULT_ARGUMENTS: include function default parameter values.
5235 TFF_EXCEPTION_SPECIFICATION: show function exception specification.
5236 TFF_TEMPLATE_HEADER: show the template<...> header in a
5237 template-declaration.
5238 TFF_TEMPLATE_NAME: show only template-name.
5239 TFF_EXPR_IN_PARENS: parenthesize expressions.
5240 TFF_NO_FUNCTION_ARGUMENTS: don't show function arguments.
5241 TFF_UNQUALIFIED_NAME: do not print the qualifying scope of the
5242 top-level entity.
5243 TFF_NO_OMIT_DEFAULT_TEMPLATE_ARGUMENTS: do not omit template arguments
5244 identical to their defaults.
5245 TFF_NO_TEMPLATE_BINDINGS: do not print information about the template
5246 arguments for a function template specialization.
5247 TFF_POINTER: we are printing a pointer type. */
5248
5249#define TFF_PLAIN_IDENTIFIER (0)
5250#define TFF_SCOPE (1)
5251#define TFF_CHASE_TYPEDEF (1 << 1)
5252#define TFF_DECL_SPECIFIERS (1 << 2)
5253#define TFF_CLASS_KEY_OR_ENUM (1 << 3)
5254#define TFF_RETURN_TYPE (1 << 4)
5255#define TFF_FUNCTION_DEFAULT_ARGUMENTS (1 << 5)
5256#define TFF_EXCEPTION_SPECIFICATION (1 << 6)
5257#define TFF_TEMPLATE_HEADER (1 << 7)
5258#define TFF_TEMPLATE_NAME (1 << 8)
5259#define TFF_EXPR_IN_PARENS (1 << 9)
5260#define TFF_NO_FUNCTION_ARGUMENTS (1 << 10)
5261#define TFF_UNQUALIFIED_NAME (1 << 11)
5262#define TFF_NO_OMIT_DEFAULT_TEMPLATE_ARGUMENTS (1 << 12)
5263#define TFF_NO_TEMPLATE_BINDINGS (1 << 13)
5264#define TFF_POINTER (1 << 14)
5265
5266/* Returns the TEMPLATE_DECL associated to a TEMPLATE_TEMPLATE_PARM
5267 node. */
5268#define TEMPLATE_TEMPLATE_PARM_TEMPLATE_DECL(NODE) \
5269 ((TREE_CODE (NODE) == BOUND_TEMPLATE_TEMPLATE_PARM) \
5270 ? TYPE_TI_TEMPLATE (NODE) \
5271 : TYPE_NAME (NODE))

5274
5275extern void init_reswords (void);

5277typedef struct GTY(()) operator_name_info_t {

5279 tree identifier;
5280 /* The name of the operator. */
5281 const char *name;

5283 const char *mangled_name;
5284 /* The arity of the operator. */
5285 int arity;
5286} operator_name_info_t;

5288/* A mapping from tree codes to operator name information. */

5290 [(int) MAX_TREE_CODES];

5293 [(int) MAX_TREE_CODES];

5295/* A type-qualifier, or bitmask therefore, using the TYPE_QUAL
5296 constants. */
5297
5298typedef int cp_cv_quals;
5299
5300/* Non-static member functions have an optional virt-specifier-seq.
5301 There is a VIRT_SPEC value for each virt-specifier.
5302 They can be combined by bitwise-or to form the complete set of
5303 virt-specifiers for a member function. */
5304enum virt_specifier
5305 {
5306 VIRT_SPEC_UNSPECIFIED = 0x0,
5307 VIRT_SPEC_FINAL = 0x1,
5308 VIRT_SPEC_OVERRIDE = 0x2
5309 };
5310
5311/* A type-qualifier, or bitmask therefore, using the VIRT_SPEC
5312 constants. */
5313
5314typedef int cp_virt_specifiers;
5315
5316/* Wherever there is a function-cv-qual, there could also be a ref-qualifier:
5317
5318 [dcl.fct]
5319 The return type, the parameter-type-list, the ref-qualifier, and
5320 the cv-qualifier-seq, but not the default arguments or the exception
5321 specification, are part of the function type.
5322
5323 REF_QUAL_NONE Ordinary member function with no ref-qualifier
5324 REF_QUAL_LVALUE Member function with the &-ref-qualifier
5325 REF_QUAL_RVALUE Member function with the &&-ref-qualifier */
5326
5327enum cp_ref_qualifier {
5328 REF_QUAL_NONE = 0,
5329 REF_QUAL_LVALUE = 1,
5330 REF_QUAL_RVALUE = 2
5331};
5332
5333/* A storage class. */
5334
5335enum cp_storage_class {
5336 /* sc_none must be zero so that zeroing a cp_decl_specifier_seq
5337 sets the storage_class field to sc_none. */
5338 sc_none = 0,
5339 sc_auto,
5340 sc_register,
5341 sc_static,
5342 sc_extern,
5343 sc_mutable
5344};
5345
5346/* An individual decl-specifier. This is used to index the array of
5347 locations for the declspecs in struct cp_decl_specifier_seq
5348 below. */
5349
5350enum cp_decl_spec {
5351 ds_first,
5352 ds_signed = ds_first,
5353 ds_unsigned,
5354 ds_short,
5355 ds_long,
5356 ds_const,
5357 ds_volatile,
5358 ds_restrict,
5359 ds_inline,
5360 ds_virtual,
5361 ds_explicit,
5362 ds_friend,
5363 ds_typedef,
5364 ds_alias,
5365 ds_constexpr,
5366 ds_complex,
5367 ds_thread,
5368 ds_type_spec,
5369 ds_redefined_builtin_type_spec,
5370 ds_attribute,
5371 ds_std_attribute,
5372 ds_storage_class,
5373 ds_long_long,
5374 ds_concept,
5375 ds_last /* This enumerator must always be the last one. */
5376};
5377
5378/* A decl-specifier-seq. */
5379
5380struct cp_decl_specifier_seq {
5381 /* An array of locations for the declaration sepecifiers, indexed by
5382 enum cp_decl_spec_word. */
5383 source_location locations[ds_last];
5384 /* The primary type, if any, given by the decl-specifier-seq.
5385 Modifiers, like "short", "const", and "unsigned" are not
5386 reflected here. This field will be a TYPE, unless a typedef-name
5387 was used, in which case it will be a TYPE_DECL. */
5388 tree type;
5389 /* The attributes, if any, provided with the specifier sequence. */
5390 tree attributes;
5391 /* The c++11 attributes that follows the type specifier. */
5392 tree std_attributes;
5393 /* If non-NULL, a built-in type that the user attempted to redefine
5394 to some other type. */
5395 tree redefined_builtin_type;
5396 /* The storage class specified -- or sc_none if no storage class was
5397 explicitly specified. */
5398 cp_storage_class storage_class;
5399 /* For the __intN declspec, this stores the index into the int_n_* arrays. */
5400 int int_n_idx;
5401 /* True iff TYPE_SPEC defines a class or enum. */
5402 BOOL_BITFIELD type_definition_p : 1;
5403 /* True iff multiple types were (erroneously) specified for this
5404 decl-specifier-seq. */
5405 BOOL_BITFIELD multiple_types_p : 1;
5406 /* True iff multiple storage classes were (erroneously) specified
5407 for this decl-specifier-seq or a combination of a storage class
5408 with a typedef specifier. */
5409 BOOL_BITFIELD conflicting_specifiers_p : 1;
5410 /* True iff at least one decl-specifier was found. */
5411 BOOL_BITFIELD any_specifiers_p : 1;
5412 /* True iff at least one type-specifier was found. */
5413 BOOL_BITFIELD any_type_specifiers_p : 1;
5414 /* True iff "int" was explicitly provided. */
5415 BOOL_BITFIELD explicit_int_p : 1;
5416 /* True iff "__intN" was explicitly provided. */
5417 BOOL_BITFIELD explicit_intN_p : 1;
5418 /* True iff "char" was explicitly provided. */
5419 BOOL_BITFIELD explicit_char_p : 1;
5420 /* True iff ds_thread is set for __thread, not thread_local. */
5421 BOOL_BITFIELD gnu_thread_keyword_p : 1;
5422 /* True iff the type is a decltype. */
5423 BOOL_BITFIELD decltype_p : 1;
5424};
5425
5426/* The various kinds of declarators. */
5427
5428enum cp_declarator_kind {
5429 cdk_id,
5430 cdk_function,
5431 cdk_array,
5432 cdk_pointer,
5433 cdk_reference,
5434 cdk_ptrmem,
5435 cdk_decomp,
5436 cdk_error
5437};
5438
5439/* A declarator. */
5440
5441typedef struct cp_declarator cp_declarator;
5442
5443typedef struct cp_parameter_declarator cp_parameter_declarator;
5444
5445/* A parameter, before it has been semantically analyzed. */
5446struct cp_parameter_declarator {
5447 /* The next parameter, or NULL_TREE if none. */
5448 cp_parameter_declarator *next;
5449 /* The decl-specifiers-seq for the parameter. */
5450 cp_decl_specifier_seq decl_specifiers;
5451 /* The declarator for the parameter. */
5452 cp_declarator *declarator;
5453 /* The default-argument expression, or NULL_TREE, if none. */
5454 tree default_argument;
5455 /* True iff this is a template parameter pack. */
5456 bool template_parameter_pack_p;
5457};
5458
5459/* A declarator. */
5460struct cp_declarator {
5461 /* The kind of declarator. */
5462 ENUM_BITFIELD (cp_declarator_kind) kind : 4;
5463 /* Whether we parsed an ellipsis (`...') just before the declarator,
5464 to indicate this is a parameter pack. */
5465 BOOL_BITFIELD parameter_pack_p : 1;
5466 location_t id_loc; /* Currently only set for cdk_id, cdk_decomp and
5467 cdk_function. */
5468 /* GNU Attributes that apply to this declarator. If the declarator
5469 is a pointer or a reference, these attribute apply to the type
5470 pointed to. */
5471 tree attributes;
5472 /* Standard C++11 attributes that apply to this declarator. If the
5473 declarator is a pointer or a reference, these attributes apply
5474 to the pointer, rather than to the type pointed to. */
5475 tree std_attributes;
5476 /* For all but cdk_id, cdk_decomp and cdk_error, the contained declarator.
5477 For cdk_id, cdk_decomp and cdk_error, guaranteed to be NULL. */
5478 cp_declarator *declarator;
5479 union {
5480 /* For identifiers. */
5481 struct {
5482 /* If non-NULL, the qualifying scope (a NAMESPACE_DECL or
5483 *_TYPE) for this identifier. */
5484 tree qualifying_scope;
5485 /* The unqualified name of the entity -- an IDENTIFIER_NODE,
5486 BIT_NOT_EXPR, or TEMPLATE_ID_EXPR. */
5487 tree unqualified_name;
5488 /* If this is the name of a function, what kind of special
5489 function (if any). */
5490 special_function_kind sfk;
5491 } id;
5492 /* For functions. */
5493 struct {
5494 /* The parameters to the function as a TREE_LIST of decl/default. */
5495 tree parameters;
5496 /* The cv-qualifiers for the function. */
5497 cp_cv_quals qualifiers;
5498 /* The virt-specifiers for the function. */
5499 cp_virt_specifiers virt_specifiers;
5500 /* The ref-qualifier for the function. */
5501 cp_ref_qualifier ref_qualifier;
5502 /* The transaction-safety qualifier for the function. */
5503 tree tx_qualifier;
5504 /* The exception-specification for the function. */
5505 tree exception_specification;
5506 /* The late-specified return type, if any. */
5507 tree late_return_type;
5508 /* The trailing requires-clause, if any. */
5509 tree requires_clause;
5510 } function;
5511 /* For arrays. */
5512 struct {
5513 /* The bounds to the array. */
5514 tree bounds;
5515 } array;
5516 /* For cdk_pointer and cdk_ptrmem. */
5517 struct {
5518 /* The cv-qualifiers for the pointer. */
5519 cp_cv_quals qualifiers;
5520 /* For cdk_ptrmem, the class type containing the member. */
5521 tree class_type;
5522 } pointer;
5523 /* For cdk_reference */
5524 struct {
5525 /* The cv-qualifiers for the reference. These qualifiers are
5526 only used to diagnose ill-formed code. */
5527 cp_cv_quals qualifiers;
5528 /* Whether this is an rvalue reference */
5529 bool rvalue_ref;
5530 } reference;
5531 } u;
5532};
5533
5534/* A level of template instantiation. */
5535struct GTY((chain_next ("%h.next"))) tinst_level {
5536 /* The immediately deeper level in the chain. */
5537 struct tinst_level *next;
5538
5539 /* The original node. Can be either a DECL (for a function or static
5540 data member) or a TYPE (for a class), depending on what we were
5541 asked to instantiate. */
5542 tree decl;
5543
5544 /* The location where the template is instantiated. */
5545 location_t locus;
5546
5547 /* errorcount+sorrycount when we pushed this level. */
5548 int errors;
5549
5550 /* True if the location is in a system header. */
5551 bool in_system_header_p;
5552};

5554bool decl_spec_seq_has_spec_p (const cp_decl_specifier_seq *, cp_decl_spec);

5556/* Return the type of the `this' parameter of FNTYPE. */
5557
5558inline tree
5559type_of_this_parm (const_tree fntype)
5560{
5561 function_args_iterator iter;
5562 gcc_assert (TREE_CODE (fntype) == METHOD_TYPE);
5563 function_args_iter_init (&iter, fntype);
5564 return function_args_iter_cond (&iter);
5565}
5566
5567/* Return the class of the `this' parameter of FNTYPE. */
5568
5569inline tree
5570class_of_this_parm (const_tree fntype)
5571{
5572 return TREE_TYPE (type_of_this_parm (fntype));
5573}
5574
5575/* True iff T is a variable template declaration. */
5576inline bool
5577variable_template_p (tree t)
5578{
5579 if (TREE_CODE (t) != TEMPLATE_DECL)
5580 return false;
5581 if (!PRIMARY_TEMPLATE_P (t))
5582 return false;
5583 if (tree r = DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT (t))
5584 return VAR_P (r);
5585 return false;
5586}
5587
5588/* True iff T is a variable concept definition. That is, T is
5589 a variable template declared with the concept specifier. */
5590inline bool
5591variable_concept_p (tree t)
5592{
5593 if (TREE_CODE (t) != TEMPLATE_DECL)
5594 return false;
5595 if (tree r = DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT (t))
5596 return VAR_P (r) && DECL_DECLARED_CONCEPT_P (r);
5597 return false;
5598}
5599
5600/* True iff T is a concept definition. That is, T is a variable or function
5601 template declared with the concept specifier. */
5602inline bool
5603concept_template_p (tree t)
5604{
5605 if (TREE_CODE (t) != TEMPLATE_DECL)
5606 return false;
5607 if (tree r = DECL_TEMPLATE_RESULT (t))
5608 return VAR_OR_FUNCTION_DECL_P (r) && DECL_DECLARED_CONCEPT_P (r);
5609 return false;
5610}

6357/* The representation of a deferred access check. */
6358
6359struct GTY(()) deferred_access_check {
6360 /* The base class in which the declaration is referenced. */
6361 tree binfo;
6362 /* The declaration whose access must be checked. */
6363 tree decl;
6364 /* The declaration that should be used in the error message. */
6365 tree diag_decl;
6366 /* The location of this access. */
6367 location_t loc;
6368};

6384/* RAII sentinel to ensures that deferred access checks are popped before
6385 a function returns. */
6386
6387struct deferring_access_check_sentinel
6388{
6389 deferring_access_check_sentinel ()
6390 {
6391 push_deferring_access_checks (dk_deferred);
6392 }
6393 ~deferring_access_check_sentinel ()
6394 {
6395 pop_deferring_access_checks ();
6396 }
6397};

6964/* Tell the binding oracle what kind of binding we are looking for. */
6965
6966enum cp_oracle_request
6967{
6968 CP_ORACLE_IDENTIFIER
6969};
6970
6971/* If this is non-NULL, then it is a "binding oracle" which can lazily
6972 create bindings when needed by the C compiler. The oracle is told
6973 the name and type of the binding to create. It can call pushdecl
6974 or the like to ensure the binding is visible; or do nothing,
6975 leaving the binding untouched. c-decl.c takes note of when the
6976 oracle has been called and will not call it again if it fails to
6977 create a given binding. */
6978
6979typedef void cp_binding_oracle_function (enum cp_oracle_request, tree identifier);
6980
6981extern cp_binding_oracle_function *cp_binding_oracle;
